WEBVTT

00:01.392 --> 00:01.610
.

00:01.653 --> 00:03.829
[bright tones]

00:03.873 --> 00:05.831
- In the criminal justice
system,

00:05.875 --> 00:07.137
sexually based offenses

00:07.181 --> 00:09.400
are considered
especially heinous.

00:09.444 --> 00:12.012
In New York City,
the dedicated detectives

00:12.055 --> 00:13.839
who investigate
these vicious felonies

00:13.883 --> 00:15.145
are members of an elite squad

00:15.189 --> 00:17.147
known as
the Special Victims Unit.

00:17.191 --> 00:19.802
These are their stories.

00:19.845 --> 00:22.326
- Come on, man, let's go!

00:22.370 --> 00:24.937
Move your car, let's go!
[phone buzzing]

00:24.981 --> 00:27.157
I know, I know.
[stammers]

00:27.201 --> 00:29.377
Parking's a bitch, man.
What do you want me to do?

00:29.420 --> 00:31.509
No, no, no,
I finally found a spot.

00:31.553 --> 00:33.337
Just five minutes
Give me five minutes.

00:33.381 --> 00:35.513
[car honks]

00:35.557 --> 00:38.560
[engine revving]

00:39.735 --> 00:42.216
Son of a bitch!

00:44.479 --> 00:46.872
Hey, you!
That was my damn spot!

00:46.916 --> 00:48.178
- Oh, you got your name on it?

00:48.222 --> 00:49.788
- You know how long
I was waiting?

00:49.832 --> 00:51.181
- You snooze, dude, you lose.

00:51.225 --> 00:52.487
- I lose?
- That's right.

00:52.530 --> 00:53.662
- Screw this.

00:53.705 --> 00:56.534
- Uncool, man.

00:56.578 --> 00:58.449
- Now move your damn car!

00:58.493 --> 01:01.539
[sirens wailing]

01:04.977 --> 01:07.023
- What's going on here?
- I'm okay.

01:07.067 --> 01:09.199
Sorry to bother you, officer.

01:09.243 --> 01:12.202
It was a misunderstanding
over a parking spot.

01:12.246 --> 01:15.031
- And your sparring partner?
- Oh, he ran that way.

01:15.075 --> 01:18.121
Scrawny guy.
I got it all right here.

01:18.165 --> 01:21.168
- Screw this.

01:21.211 --> 01:24.040
- Uncool, man.

01:24.910 --> 01:27.435
- Well, it appears
you initiated physical contact.

01:27.478 --> 01:29.741
- It's not how it looks.
You had to be there.

01:29.785 --> 01:32.179
I was waiting for the spot
and the prick noses his way in.

01:32.222 --> 01:34.268
- Is that his car?
- It is.

01:34.311 --> 01:37.401
- Andie, take a look.

01:37.445 --> 01:40.012
Look, I'll run your name.
Will I find anything?

01:40.056 --> 01:41.101
- Nothing.

01:41.144 --> 01:43.146
I'm the guy that stayed, right?

01:43.190 --> 01:44.582
The prick ran.

01:44.626 --> 01:47.759
- Well, your attitude
isn't inspiring confidence.

01:47.803 --> 01:48.978
- The guy was just rude.

01:49.021 --> 01:50.501
He gave me the finger.

01:50.545 --> 01:51.676
[metallic bang]

01:51.720 --> 01:53.591
- That's no excuse
for fisticuffs, sir.

01:53.635 --> 01:54.940
[bang]

01:54.984 --> 01:58.074
[trunk pops]

01:58.118 --> 02:00.250
[tense music]

02:00.294 --> 02:03.123
- Perry, get your ass
over here!

02:03.166 --> 02:06.300
Central, we're gonna need a bus
on North Basin, and call SVU.

02:06.343 --> 02:09.346
- Oh, jeez.
Come on.

02:09.390 --> 02:11.261
- Daddy!

02:11.305 --> 02:13.176
Daddy!
- It's okay.

02:13.220 --> 02:15.091
We're gonna take care of you.

02:15.135 --> 02:17.137
- Her name is Bailey Shaw.
She's six years old.

02:17.180 --> 02:19.051
Her parents are Griffin Shaw
and Jamie Johnston.

02:19.095 --> 02:20.836
- Okay, does Griffin drive
a silver Saturn?

02:20.879 --> 02:23.143
- No, Jamie took Bailey
ice skating

02:23.186 --> 02:24.144
in Central Park, right?

02:24.187 --> 02:25.188
And he went to the bathroom,

02:25.232 --> 02:26.972
and when he came back
she was gone.

02:27.016 --> 02:28.452
- Hey.

02:28.496 --> 02:29.584
How's she doing?

02:29.627 --> 02:31.238
- [sighs]
We've got her on fluids.

02:31.281 --> 02:32.587
She's cold, hungry.

02:32.630 --> 02:34.893
Looks like she was in
that trunk for a while.

02:34.937 --> 02:37.287
Oh, and when she got here,
her pants were on inside-out.

02:37.331 --> 02:39.115
- Did you run a rape kit?

02:39.159 --> 02:40.464
- No signs of penetration
or foreign fluids.

02:40.508 --> 02:41.770
- Can we talk to her?
- Sure.

02:41.813 --> 02:43.989
But I have to warn you,
she's pretty scared.

02:44.033 --> 02:46.078
- Okay, thanks.
Thanks, doc.

02:46.122 --> 02:47.732
- [sighs]

02:47.776 --> 02:49.821
- Hey, Bailey.

02:49.865 --> 02:51.301
My name is Olivia,

02:51.345 --> 02:53.869
and this is Amanda.

02:53.912 --> 02:56.480
- Are you doctors too?

02:56.524 --> 02:59.222
- No, no, we're actually
police officers.

02:59.266 --> 03:01.616
- I'm Bailey's father,
Griffin Shaw.

03:01.659 --> 03:03.095
- Hey.
- Hi.

03:03.139 --> 03:05.097
- I don't want to go to jail.

03:05.141 --> 03:07.230
- No, no, we're here
to help you.

03:07.274 --> 03:10.494
- Yeah, we just want to know
what happened to you.

03:11.539 --> 03:14.019
- Daddy told me
to wait for him,

03:14.063 --> 03:16.108
but I walked away with the man.

03:16.152 --> 03:19.242
- No, baby,
it wasn't your fault.

03:19.286 --> 03:22.376
- This man, did you know him?

03:23.377 --> 03:26.031
- He gave me a candy apple.

03:26.075 --> 03:28.817
He said he was a friend
of Daddy's.

03:28.860 --> 03:30.427
He was nice.

03:30.471 --> 03:33.256
He let me wear his scarf
to get warm.

03:33.300 --> 03:36.041
It was yellow like Big Bird.

03:36.085 --> 03:38.043
- Uh-huh, and then--

03:38.087 --> 03:40.611
and then he took you somewhere?

03:40.655 --> 03:44.398
- He said we could wait
for Daddy in his car.

03:44.441 --> 03:48.053
It was better
than standing in the cold.

03:48.097 --> 03:49.881
But then we drove off.

03:49.925 --> 03:52.406
He said Daddy would meet us.

03:52.449 --> 03:54.146
- And where did he take you?

03:54.190 --> 03:56.323
- To his house, I think.

03:56.366 --> 03:58.760
- And what did you do
when you got there?

03:58.803 --> 04:01.980
- We took off our clothes
and took a nap.

04:02.024 --> 04:03.547
- Oh, my God.

04:03.591 --> 04:06.550
- So, Bailey,
did he tell you his name?

04:06.594 --> 04:08.291
♪

04:08.335 --> 04:10.989
- He said I could
call him Big Bird,

04:11.033 --> 04:13.035
but I thought that was silly.

04:13.078 --> 04:15.690
- [sighs]

04:15.733 --> 04:18.301
- Did you play
any games with him

04:18.345 --> 04:20.216
before you took the nap?

04:20.260 --> 04:21.652
- No.

04:21.696 --> 04:25.177
I was cold so we just snuggled
under the blankets.

04:25.221 --> 04:28.137
- Excuse me.

04:28.180 --> 04:30.574
- My husband, Jamie.

04:30.618 --> 04:32.794
- Baby.

04:32.837 --> 04:34.839
- I'm okay.

04:34.883 --> 04:36.928
I'm sorry, Daddy.

04:36.972 --> 04:40.192
- No, no, no,
you didn't do anything wrong.

04:40.236 --> 04:46.111
♪

04:46.155 --> 04:49.114
[dramatic music]

04:49.158 --> 04:56.339
♪

05:32.636 --> 05:34.508
- Fin, where do we stand?

05:34.551 --> 05:37.380
- CSU pulled prints
off the Saturn, no hits.

05:37.424 --> 05:39.643
- Well, what about
the cellphone video?

05:39.687 --> 05:41.210
- With TARU.

05:41.253 --> 05:42.864
We may get lucky and get a hit
on the facial recognition.

05:42.907 --> 05:46.171
I called in an arrest-for
in all five boroughs.

05:46.215 --> 05:47.608
He can run,
but he can't hide, Liv.

05:47.651 --> 05:49.349
- The registered owner
of the Saturn

05:49.392 --> 05:50.741
died two weeks ago.

05:50.785 --> 05:53.048
His son sold it
in an estate sale last week.

05:53.091 --> 05:54.571
- Okay, what about
the new owner?

05:54.615 --> 05:55.659
- He's a mystery man.

05:55.703 --> 05:56.878
He saw the sign
on the car window,

05:56.921 --> 05:58.096
he knocked on the door,
he paid all cash.

05:58.140 --> 05:59.489
He never registered the title.

05:59.533 --> 06:01.491
- Guys, we're talking about
a six year old girl

06:01.535 --> 06:03.275
who was grabbed
in Central Park.

06:03.319 --> 06:05.930
Somebody must have
seen something.

06:05.974 --> 06:07.410
- We already canvassed.

06:07.454 --> 06:10.370
- Then canvass again.

06:10.413 --> 06:12.241
[phones ringing]

06:12.284 --> 06:13.503
- I have to ask:

06:13.547 --> 06:15.331
Is there anyone in your lives
who might--

06:15.375 --> 06:16.680
- Wait, wait, you think--

06:16.724 --> 06:18.029
you think someone
we know did this.

06:18.073 --> 06:20.336
- No, absolutely not.

06:20.380 --> 06:22.120
- Okay, well, guys,
I'm gonna get personal.

06:22.164 --> 06:23.513
- Anything to catch this guy.

06:23.557 --> 06:25.515
- Was Bailey adopted?

06:25.559 --> 06:27.430
- Yes.
- And no.

06:27.474 --> 06:28.605
- You're gonna have to explain.

06:28.649 --> 06:30.955
- We used a surrogate
with my sperm.

06:30.999 --> 06:32.217
- And I adopted her.

06:32.261 --> 06:34.089
- The surrogate, would she--
- No, no, no.

06:34.132 --> 06:36.657
Paige isn't like that.
- No.

06:36.700 --> 06:38.354
- She wouldn't be
the first surrogate

06:38.398 --> 06:40.487
to change her mind.

06:40.530 --> 06:43.925
- She wouldn't.

06:43.968 --> 06:46.101
Do you think?

06:49.800 --> 06:52.760
- Once Bailey was born,
I relinquished all my rights

06:52.803 --> 06:54.675
to the birth father,
Griffin Shaw.

06:54.718 --> 06:56.894
- And you were never curious?

06:56.938 --> 06:58.287
- Of course I was.

06:58.330 --> 06:59.984
I carried that baby
for nine months,

07:00.028 --> 07:01.682
but a deal's a deal.

07:01.725 --> 07:03.074
The agency prepared me.

07:03.118 --> 07:05.425
Counselors and shrinks,
the whole nine yards.

07:05.468 --> 07:07.557
Did something happen to Bailey?

07:07.601 --> 07:09.429
- She's fine now.

07:09.472 --> 07:11.561
Is your boyfriend home?

07:11.605 --> 07:14.477
- What does he have
to do with anything?

07:14.521 --> 07:16.958
You know what, I--I don't like
the way this is going.

07:17.001 --> 07:20.265
[phone buzzes]

07:20.309 --> 07:22.050
- You mind if I take
a look at that?

07:22.093 --> 07:23.355
- I do.

07:23.399 --> 07:25.967
- Okay, Paige, so let me
tell you where we stand.

07:26.010 --> 07:27.490
I can take you down
to the squad room,

07:27.534 --> 07:29.057
where you're gonna sit
and you're gonna wait

07:29.100 --> 07:31.755
until Detective Rollins
gets you a search warrant.

07:31.799 --> 07:34.410
- Then we'll be in the exact
same position we are now

07:34.454 --> 07:36.847
except I will be
extremely pissed off

07:36.891 --> 07:38.675
'cause you would have wasted
two hours of my life.

07:38.719 --> 07:40.677
- All right, so how about
you unlock the phone

07:40.721 --> 07:43.506
and open the photo app.

07:43.550 --> 07:45.421
[phone clicks]

07:45.465 --> 07:48.424
[foreboding music]

07:48.468 --> 07:50.513
♪

07:50.557 --> 07:53.124
Paige, you are under arrest.

07:53.168 --> 07:55.300
- What? Why?

07:55.344 --> 07:56.693
- Stalking, for starters,

07:56.737 --> 07:58.086
and I'm betting we're gonna
tack on kidnapping.

07:58.129 --> 08:00.175
- What, it's a crime to take
pictures of my daughter?

08:00.218 --> 08:02.438
- Hey, Fin.
Where?

08:02.482 --> 08:03.831
- This is the part
where you have the right

08:03.874 --> 08:05.093
to remain silent.

08:05.136 --> 08:06.573
- I'm on my way.

08:06.616 --> 08:09.184
Uh, Fin, they got a hit
on the driver of the Saturn.

08:09.227 --> 08:11.795
I'll get this, you take her
down to the squad room.

08:11.839 --> 08:13.101
- Come on.

08:13.144 --> 08:14.798
- Fin.

08:14.842 --> 08:17.975
- Off-duty cop stopped
at the bodega on the way home.

08:18.019 --> 08:19.803
He spotted our guy
buying some Marlboros.

08:19.847 --> 08:22.327
He was unarmed, so he stepped
outside and called it in.

08:22.371 --> 08:23.894
- He still inside?

08:23.938 --> 08:25.592
- When the officer went inside
to confront him,

08:25.635 --> 08:26.767
he pulled a switchblade on him.

08:26.810 --> 08:29.073
He's now holding
the bodega owner hostage.

08:29.117 --> 08:32.424
- ESU is on the way.

08:32.468 --> 08:34.122
- Is there a back door?

08:34.165 --> 08:35.384
- Uh, odds are.

08:35.427 --> 08:37.517
Why?

08:37.560 --> 08:40.998
♪

08:41.042 --> 08:42.522
[plastic crinkling]

08:42.565 --> 08:44.915
- Who are you?

08:44.959 --> 08:47.831
- You running a book?
- Get out of here.

08:47.875 --> 08:49.877
- Yeah, not without my Oreos.
- Just go someplace else.

08:49.920 --> 08:53.184
- Hey, sweetheart, I've had
a very bad day, okay?

08:53.228 --> 08:55.360
♪

08:55.404 --> 08:57.449
I know I have cash
in here somewhere.

08:57.493 --> 08:59.321
- It's on the house.

08:59.364 --> 09:02.367
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

09:02.411 --> 09:03.586
- That okay with you?

09:03.630 --> 09:05.588
- Yeah, yeah, I'm good.

09:05.632 --> 09:07.982
- Okay, that's a first.
- Just get out of here.

09:08.025 --> 09:11.463
- Oh, um, sorry, can I just
get some aspirin?

09:11.507 --> 09:12.943
- And that's it.

09:12.987 --> 09:15.511
- Thank you.

09:15.555 --> 09:18.253
- Drop the knife.

09:18.296 --> 09:21.256
[dramatic music]

09:21.299 --> 09:23.998
♪

09:24.041 --> 09:27.479
[both grunting]

09:27.523 --> 09:29.786
- Drop it!

09:29.830 --> 09:33.050
♪

09:33.094 --> 09:37.185
Looks like we're both
having a bad day, huh?

09:41.624 --> 09:42.016
.

09:42.059 --> 09:44.235
- Could have taken any car.

09:44.279 --> 09:45.846
I had to take the one
with the baby in the trunk.

09:45.889 --> 09:46.934
- Some guys are just unlucky.

09:46.977 --> 09:48.544
- Do you believe me?
- No.

09:48.588 --> 09:49.806
Where'd you boost that car?

09:49.850 --> 09:52.156
- Parking lot from a minimart
in Jamaica.

09:52.200 --> 09:55.246
God, man, God.

09:55.290 --> 09:57.161
Look, I'm a lowlife.

09:57.205 --> 09:59.120
Scumbag car thief, okay?
I admit it.

09:59.163 --> 10:01.992
- A 2003 Saturn.
You're not a good one.

10:02.036 --> 10:02.950
- See?

10:02.993 --> 10:04.212
Everyone knows
that I'm a moron.

10:04.255 --> 10:05.909
I'm way--I'm way too stupid
to kidnap someone.

10:05.953 --> 10:07.215
There's no way
I could have done it.

10:07.258 --> 10:08.825
I was with my girl all morning.

10:08.869 --> 10:10.522
I was with Lee Anne.

10:10.566 --> 10:11.567
That's why I took the wheel.

10:11.611 --> 10:12.829
She was late
for her job interview.

10:12.873 --> 10:15.658
I dropped her, I stopped
for a pack of smokes.

10:15.702 --> 10:17.442
That's when that maniac
slugged me.

10:17.486 --> 10:18.618
- That might have been

10:18.661 --> 10:21.490
the best thing
to happen to you.

10:22.926 --> 10:24.188
- She's a part of me.

10:24.232 --> 10:25.755
- That doesn't mean
you can take her, Paige.

10:25.799 --> 10:26.843
- How many times
do I have to say it?

10:26.887 --> 10:28.192
I didn't take her.

10:28.236 --> 10:30.542
- Okay, you just took pictures.

10:30.586 --> 10:33.023
Okay.

10:33.067 --> 10:34.851
These are from your phone.

10:34.895 --> 10:36.679
They were all taken
in Central Park

10:36.723 --> 10:39.203
the day Bailey was kidnapped.

10:39.247 --> 10:41.989
- I would never do anything
to hurt Bailey.

10:42.032 --> 10:45.819
Or Griffin or Jamie.

10:45.862 --> 10:49.866
I just like looking at her.
[sniffles]

10:49.910 --> 10:52.564
- Pretty hard to believe.

10:52.608 --> 10:55.306
[tense music]

10:55.350 --> 10:58.832
- [sniffles]

10:58.875 --> 11:00.921
I needed money.

11:00.964 --> 11:03.706
For tuition.

11:03.750 --> 11:05.186
I thought it'd be no big deal.

11:05.229 --> 11:06.709
I--I have plenty of eggs.

11:06.753 --> 11:08.711
Might as well
make somebody happy.

11:08.755 --> 11:11.409
♪

11:11.453 --> 11:12.889
[sniffles]

11:12.933 --> 11:16.545
I carried her for nine months.

11:16.588 --> 11:19.113
I sang to her when she kicked.

11:19.156 --> 11:21.681
Her blood is my blood.

11:21.724 --> 11:24.727
That scar will always be there.

11:24.771 --> 11:27.687
[sniffles]
- [sighs]

11:27.730 --> 11:29.732
♪

11:29.776 --> 11:31.734
[papers shuffling]

11:31.778 --> 11:39.002
♪

11:40.134 --> 11:41.962
- Hey, Lieu, we're wasting
our time here.

11:42.005 --> 11:44.007
Bailey couldn't ID photos
of either one of them.

11:44.051 --> 11:46.401
- Well, I was kinda rooting
for Mr. Wonderful.

11:46.444 --> 11:47.707
- Yeah, Soren West.

11:47.750 --> 11:49.317
He's got two outstanding
warrants for possession.

11:49.360 --> 11:52.189
- Oh, well, tack on auto theft,
assaulting a police officer,

11:52.233 --> 11:54.148
and get him in Rikers.
- Okay.

11:54.191 --> 11:56.324
- Hey, Paige may have
given us something.

11:56.367 --> 11:58.326
- I--I don't think Paige
is involved in this.

11:58.369 --> 12:00.632
- She may have helped us
find the guy who is.

12:00.676 --> 12:03.287
So she took this picture
of Bailey in Central Park,

12:03.331 --> 12:05.072
and Bailey said that--
that the kidnapper

12:05.115 --> 12:06.813
reminded her
of Big Bird because--

12:06.856 --> 12:07.944
- Because he was wearing
a yellow scarf.

12:07.988 --> 12:09.424
- Paige doesn't know
who this is but--

12:09.467 --> 12:11.121
- At least now we know
what he looks like.

12:11.165 --> 12:14.298
- All right, so see how CSU
is doing with that Saturn.

12:16.431 --> 12:18.520
- I've been through it
soup to nuts.

12:18.563 --> 12:21.523
- Tell us you found something.
- Just the usual garbage.

12:21.566 --> 12:23.264
Help yourself.

12:23.307 --> 12:25.353
[car back-up alarm beeping]

12:25.396 --> 12:27.268
- Well, we know he's not
a health nut.

12:27.311 --> 12:30.662
- That narrows it down.

12:30.706 --> 12:32.577
- Did you look in here?

12:32.621 --> 12:34.405
- Why would I care
about leftover coffee?

12:34.449 --> 12:37.365
- 'Cause sometimes
it's a garbage can.

12:40.847 --> 12:42.805
It's a parking lot ticket.

12:42.849 --> 12:43.937
310 East 11th Street.

12:43.980 --> 12:47.027
This was timestamped
two days ago.

12:49.986 --> 12:51.509
Hey, wake up.

12:51.553 --> 12:54.512
- Nap time's over.

12:54.556 --> 12:56.776
- You got a ticket?

13:00.649 --> 13:03.826
Uh, cops, sure.
Take any spot, on the house.

13:03.870 --> 13:04.958
- You know this guy?

13:05.001 --> 13:06.829
- You know how many people
park here?

13:06.873 --> 13:10.050
- He was here two days ago.

13:12.095 --> 13:13.836
- Patsy's Puppets,
down the block.

13:13.880 --> 13:15.707
- He told you
where he was going?

13:15.751 --> 13:17.971
- No, it's got a green
validation stamp on it.

13:18.014 --> 13:19.886
It's the puppet theater.

13:19.929 --> 13:21.801
- All right, thanks.

13:21.844 --> 13:24.151
- Here you go.
Thanks for coming!

13:24.194 --> 13:26.457
Bye, come again!

13:26.501 --> 13:27.589
Uh--oh, hi.

13:27.632 --> 13:29.373
Can I help you?
- Uh, yeah, you can.

13:29.417 --> 13:32.072
I'm, uh--I'm looking for a guy
who came in the other day.

13:32.115 --> 13:33.856
- [gasps]
He's a cop, Marv.

13:33.900 --> 13:35.031
I'll handle this, Harv.

13:35.075 --> 13:36.641
It's a shakedown.
[babbles]

13:36.685 --> 13:39.209
- Look, if you don't look
at this photo, I'm gonna shake

13:39.253 --> 13:41.429
your little friend
by his neck, okay?

13:41.472 --> 13:43.910
- Oh, yeah, yeah, sure.
He came in here.

13:43.953 --> 13:45.302
Uh, applied for a job.

13:45.346 --> 13:48.653
Guy was kind of, uh, off,
you know?

13:48.697 --> 13:50.003
- He was off.
- Mm-hmm.

13:50.046 --> 13:51.352
- You remember his name?

13:51.395 --> 13:53.354
- No, but he filled out
a full application.

13:53.397 --> 13:54.877
Name, address,
the whole kit and caboodle.

13:54.921 --> 13:58.011
Uh, I'll go get it.

13:58.054 --> 14:00.578
- [scoffs]

14:01.971 --> 14:03.059
- Hope they don't
have puppets.

14:03.103 --> 14:04.191
I hate puppets.

14:04.234 --> 14:05.801
- I thought they were
kind of funny.

14:05.845 --> 14:07.847
- Arrogant bastards.

14:07.890 --> 14:10.327
[doorbell rings]

14:11.372 --> 14:13.896
- Hi, I'm Detective Carisi.
This is Sergeant Tutuola.

14:13.940 --> 14:15.245
Does Emerson Mauer live here?

14:15.289 --> 14:17.900
- That's my son.
Something happen to him?

14:17.944 --> 14:19.641
- Oh, he's fine.
We just want to talk to him.

14:19.684 --> 14:21.686
- Well, he should be here
any minute.

14:21.730 --> 14:24.820
You--you want to come in?
- Yeah, that'd be great.

14:24.864 --> 14:27.301
- You sure you don't want
some tea?

14:27.344 --> 14:29.869
My husband got me hooked
on green tea.

14:29.912 --> 14:31.131
- No, we're great.

14:31.174 --> 14:32.393
Um, is your husband around?

14:32.436 --> 14:35.048
- Nah, he ran off years ago.

14:35.091 --> 14:37.224
- Oh, well, we're sorry
to hear that.

14:37.267 --> 14:39.052
So where's your boy work?

14:39.095 --> 14:40.967
- At the paint store.

14:41.010 --> 14:44.231
He's looking
for something else, but...

14:45.058 --> 14:47.277
Oh, I bet this is
about his car.

14:47.321 --> 14:48.888
- Actually, it is.

14:48.931 --> 14:50.759
- Yeah, somebody stole it.

14:50.802 --> 14:52.413
What's the world coming to?

14:52.456 --> 14:54.328
- Was, uh--was your son
at work on Wednesday?

14:54.371 --> 14:57.592
- Nah, it's his day off.

14:57.635 --> 15:00.116
- That's great, you got
to spend all day together.

15:00.160 --> 15:01.552
- I wish.

15:01.596 --> 15:03.076
I asked for Wednesdays off,

15:03.119 --> 15:05.992
but Mr. Lichtman's got steel
where his heart should be.

15:06.035 --> 15:06.993
- Huh.

15:07.036 --> 15:08.429
- I'm home!

15:08.472 --> 15:09.517
- Hey.

15:09.560 --> 15:11.954
- Hey, I didn't know
you had company.

15:11.998 --> 15:13.956
- Emerson Mauer?

15:14.000 --> 15:15.218
- Yes.

15:15.262 --> 15:16.611
- We just wanna talk to you
for a little bit

15:16.654 --> 15:19.657
about Bailey Shaw.

15:19.701 --> 15:20.963
[dramatic music]

15:21.007 --> 15:23.705
- Wait!
Hey, hey!

15:23.748 --> 15:25.489
♪

15:25.533 --> 15:27.535
- [grunts]

15:27.578 --> 15:29.754
[both grunt]

15:29.798 --> 15:31.669
[cuffs clicking]

15:31.713 --> 15:32.801
- Forgot to tell you,

15:32.844 --> 15:34.020
you're under arrest
for kidnapping.

15:34.063 --> 15:36.979
Get up.
- [whines]

15:37.023 --> 15:40.765
♪

15:40.809 --> 15:42.680
Mom!

15:42.724 --> 15:44.856
[car door opens]

15:47.990 --> 15:48.338
.

15:48.382 --> 15:50.688
- So I like to go
to Central Park on my days off.

15:50.732 --> 15:52.299
- You like to look
at the kids, do you?

15:52.342 --> 15:54.170
- You know it's, uh,
one of the first major

15:54.214 --> 15:55.824
landscape parks in the country?

15:55.867 --> 15:57.260
- I didn't know that.

15:57.304 --> 15:59.306
- Well, there are
29 unique statues.

15:59.349 --> 16:02.222
The, uh, 57-horse carousel
is one of the nation's largest.

16:02.265 --> 16:04.789
The whole park was once
entirely covered by glaciers.

16:04.833 --> 16:07.705
- Hmm, and a lot of kids
hang out there, too...

16:07.749 --> 16:09.272
including Bailey Shaw.

16:09.316 --> 16:10.534
- I told you, I don't know her.

16:10.578 --> 16:11.840
- [scoffs]
Okay, so you're telling me

16:11.883 --> 16:15.365
that somehow she locked herself
in your trunk?

16:15.409 --> 16:16.976
- This is getting boring.

16:17.019 --> 16:20.153
I repeat: My car was stolen
from the minimart parking lot,

16:20.196 --> 16:22.329
so surely it was the thief
who put her there.

16:22.372 --> 16:24.722
- Hmm.
That's not what he says.

16:24.766 --> 16:27.334
- What, you caught him?
- Yeah, we did.

16:27.377 --> 16:29.118
- And you believe a felon
over me.

16:29.162 --> 16:30.380
- Well, first of all, Emerson,

16:30.424 --> 16:32.034
you can't judge a book
by its cover.

16:32.078 --> 16:35.559
Second, you never reported
that car stolen.

16:37.083 --> 16:39.563
I wonder why that is?

16:42.349 --> 16:44.699
- As it stands, I'm pretty sure
I can get an indictment,

16:44.742 --> 16:46.788
but a conviction's
a whole other ball game.

16:46.831 --> 16:48.268
- Okay, well, how does it look
for a search warrant?

16:48.311 --> 16:49.747
- DNA?
- No.

16:49.791 --> 16:50.835
- Hair sample?

16:50.879 --> 16:52.924
- That's why we need
a search warrant.

16:52.968 --> 16:54.317
That's Bailey and her parents.

16:54.361 --> 16:56.145
- You get me one thing
that's not circumstantial,

16:56.189 --> 16:59.148
I'll get you a warrant.

16:59.192 --> 17:00.932
Thank you for coming,
gentlemen.

17:00.976 --> 17:02.064
Hi.

17:02.108 --> 17:04.066
You must be Bailey.

17:04.110 --> 17:05.763
My name's Peter.
I'm a lawyer.

17:05.807 --> 17:08.549
- Are you going to put
the bad man in jail?

17:08.592 --> 17:10.725
- I'm gonna do my best, Bailey.

17:10.768 --> 17:12.466
- Thank you, Peter.

17:12.509 --> 17:15.991
- So the good news is,
is we think we have him.

17:16.035 --> 17:18.080
- Good.

17:18.124 --> 17:21.127
- Bailey, I bet
you like puzzles.

17:21.170 --> 17:23.303
Is that true?

17:23.346 --> 17:24.826
'Cause we have a whole bunch
of them in that room

17:24.869 --> 17:25.827
right over there.

17:25.870 --> 17:27.176
- Can I?

17:27.220 --> 17:30.266
- Of course.
- Okay.

17:30.310 --> 17:32.225
[phones ringing]

17:32.268 --> 17:33.704
- She seems to be doing well.

17:33.748 --> 17:35.358
- If you ignore
the night screams.

17:35.402 --> 17:37.230
- What's his name?

17:37.273 --> 17:39.101
- Emerson Mauer.
- Never heard of him.

17:39.145 --> 17:40.320
- Nor I.

17:40.363 --> 17:41.451
- So he's just
some random pervert, then?

17:41.495 --> 17:42.800
- You're not helping, Jamie.

17:42.844 --> 17:45.107
- She said they got naked
and got into bed.

17:45.151 --> 17:48.502
She's six years old.
That's perverted.

17:48.545 --> 17:51.200
- He told me I was
his big girl.

17:51.244 --> 17:54.421
- Oh, and when
did he tell you that?

17:54.464 --> 17:57.119
- When we were in his bed.

17:57.163 --> 18:00.209
He pressed up against me.

18:00.253 --> 18:03.038
- Did that...scare you?

18:03.082 --> 18:04.692
- No.

18:04.735 --> 18:07.956
He was nice.

18:07.999 --> 18:11.090
- So, Bailey, can you...

18:11.133 --> 18:14.267
♪

18:14.310 --> 18:16.965
Can you show me
how he did that?

18:17.008 --> 18:24.015
♪

18:30.848 --> 18:32.763
So your clothes were off?

18:32.807 --> 18:36.115
- Yes.

18:36.158 --> 18:38.421
- Mm-hmm.

18:38.465 --> 18:40.815
So this--this is how
you were dressed?

18:40.858 --> 18:42.251
- Yes.

18:42.295 --> 18:44.949
- And you were in the bed?

18:44.993 --> 18:47.735
♪

18:47.778 --> 18:49.302
- Like that.

18:49.345 --> 18:51.260
He squeezed me tight,

18:51.304 --> 18:54.220
but when I said it hurt,
he stopped.

18:54.263 --> 18:56.222
♪

18:56.265 --> 18:57.527
Where are my daddies?

18:57.571 --> 18:59.268
- You know, they're
right outside, honey.

18:59.312 --> 19:01.227
Um, if it's okay with you,

19:01.270 --> 19:04.186
I just want play
one more game, okay?

19:04.230 --> 19:06.101
Just real fast.

19:06.145 --> 19:07.668
- Okay.
- Come here, sweetie.

19:07.711 --> 19:10.671
Um, I'm just gonna show you
a couple of pictures,

19:10.714 --> 19:13.674
and you tell me
if you recognize anyone.

19:13.717 --> 19:15.197
- Okay.

19:15.241 --> 19:18.113
♪

19:18.157 --> 19:20.202
He's funny-looking.
- Yeah?

19:20.246 --> 19:22.161
Do you know him?

19:22.204 --> 19:24.859
♪

19:24.902 --> 19:26.339
What about him?

19:26.382 --> 19:28.210
- Nope.

19:28.254 --> 19:30.865
♪

19:30.908 --> 19:32.214
That's him.

19:32.258 --> 19:34.260
That's Big Bird.

19:34.303 --> 19:36.349
♪

19:36.392 --> 19:38.568
- Good, honey.

19:38.612 --> 19:41.441
Good.

19:41.484 --> 19:43.834
Bailey ID'd a photo of Emerson.

19:43.878 --> 19:47.621
That should convince a jury
of the bastard's peers.

19:47.664 --> 19:50.537
- Hold on, we're not gonna
let her testify.

19:50.580 --> 19:53.192
No way, absolutely not.

19:53.235 --> 19:54.236
- Without your
daughter's testimony,

19:54.280 --> 19:55.281
we don't have a case.

19:55.324 --> 19:56.456
- All those people
staring at her?

19:56.499 --> 19:58.545
Not a chance.

19:58.588 --> 20:00.329
She's not going to court,
and that's all we have to say.

20:00.373 --> 20:02.592
- She can testify
by video conference.

20:02.636 --> 20:04.725
- But his lawyer gets
to question her.

20:04.768 --> 20:08.642
- I'm sure that you don't want
Mr. Mauer doing this

20:08.685 --> 20:10.513
to another little girl.

20:10.557 --> 20:12.080
- Of course not, but we're
not going to subject

20:12.123 --> 20:13.560
our baby girl to more trauma.

20:13.603 --> 20:15.866
A defense attorney
ripping her story apart?

20:15.910 --> 20:18.913
No, it's better
she forget the whole thing.

20:18.956 --> 20:23.265
- The next little girl
may not be as lucky as Bailey.

20:23.309 --> 20:24.745
- Griffin, help me out.

20:24.788 --> 20:28.270
- The truth is,
for obvious reasons,

20:28.314 --> 20:30.620
Bailey has a much harder time
than most kids.

20:30.664 --> 20:33.275
We go to a school play,
we get stared at.

20:33.319 --> 20:34.668
And not just by the children.

20:34.711 --> 20:36.278
- That's all in your head.

20:36.322 --> 20:39.542
- Still, kids can be very mean.

20:39.586 --> 20:41.544
Something like this
can leave more scars.

20:41.588 --> 20:43.154
- Okay, this may be
the only way--

20:43.198 --> 20:46.114
- I'm sorry, as far as we're
concerned, this is over.

20:46.157 --> 20:48.595
[tense music]

20:48.638 --> 20:51.293
- Let's get her home.

20:51.337 --> 20:57.517
♪

20:58.648 --> 20:59.954
- So much for that.

20:59.997 --> 21:01.521
- I can still swear
in an affidavit

21:01.564 --> 21:03.349
that she ID'd Mauer.

21:03.392 --> 21:04.567
- Liv--

21:04.611 --> 21:07.440
- It'll get us a warrant
to search his house.

21:07.483 --> 21:09.224
♪

21:09.268 --> 21:10.399
- This is harassment!

21:10.443 --> 21:12.053
I'm gonna sue you!

21:12.096 --> 21:13.620
- Wouldn't be the first.

21:13.663 --> 21:15.186
- We pay our taxes!

21:15.230 --> 21:17.624
- That's enough to keep your
son in oatmeal at Sing Sing.

21:17.667 --> 21:19.843
- Emerson didn't do anything!

21:19.887 --> 21:21.628
- That's not what
the witness says.

21:21.671 --> 21:23.456
- What, are you gonna believe
a six-year-old?

21:23.499 --> 21:24.500
- A six-year-old eyewitness?

21:24.544 --> 21:26.110
Yeah.
- Well, a jury won't.

21:26.154 --> 21:28.330
- Found a t-shirt in the bureau
in his bedroom.

21:28.374 --> 21:29.897
About the right size
for a first-grader.

21:29.940 --> 21:32.029
- Maybe they'll believe
two six-year-olds.

21:32.073 --> 21:34.467
- You got a garage in the back.
What's in there?

21:34.510 --> 21:35.598
- It was my husband's!

21:35.642 --> 21:37.383
God only knows
what he did in there!

21:37.426 --> 21:38.645
- You got a key?

21:38.688 --> 21:39.994
- I wouldn't even know
where to look.

21:40.037 --> 21:42.475
- I'll get bolt cutters.
- Old tools and junk!

21:42.518 --> 21:44.259
That's all you're gonna
find in there.

21:44.303 --> 21:46.435
- We'd like to see
for ourselves.

21:46.479 --> 21:49.438
[suspenseful music]

21:49.482 --> 21:55.488
♪

21:55.531 --> 21:58.491
- I'll get CSU.

21:58.534 --> 22:04.888
♪

22:04.932 --> 22:07.456
- This is fescue.
- God bless you.

22:07.500 --> 22:09.197
- It's a type of grass.

22:09.240 --> 22:10.372
- So?

22:10.416 --> 22:11.852
- So this is fescue, but this--

22:11.895 --> 22:13.114
this spot is
Kentucky bluegrass.

22:13.157 --> 22:15.377
- Who are you, "Mary, Mary,
Quite Contrary"?

22:15.421 --> 22:17.292
- We had fescue growing up.

22:17.336 --> 22:19.947
Yankee Stadium
had Kentucky blue.

22:19.990 --> 22:22.515
Why would somebody need
two different types of grass?

22:22.558 --> 22:23.907
- Maybe they just didn't know

22:23.951 --> 22:26.040
and got the wrong kind
of grass seed.

22:26.083 --> 22:29.304
- Yeah, but why would you need
to seed a 3 x 5 foot patch?

22:29.348 --> 22:36.572
♪

22:39.923 --> 22:42.317
- Detectives,
we got something.

22:42.361 --> 22:45.407
♪

22:45.451 --> 22:47.409
[radio chatter]

22:47.453 --> 22:50.934
♪

22:50.978 --> 22:53.415
- It's a skull.

22:53.459 --> 22:55.504
- A kid's skull.

22:55.548 --> 22:57.811
[sighs]

22:57.854 --> 23:04.905
♪

23:13.566 --> 23:13.783
.

23:13.827 --> 23:15.481
- What did I tell you
about my ex?

23:15.524 --> 23:16.786
Once a bum, always a bum.

23:16.830 --> 23:18.745
- You had a kid's bones
in your backyard.

23:18.788 --> 23:20.834
I think that qualifies you
as something much worse

23:20.877 --> 23:22.139
than a bum, Mrs. Mauer.

23:22.183 --> 23:23.619
- Me?

23:23.663 --> 23:25.578
- Why'd you squirm when I asked
you what was back there?

23:25.621 --> 23:27.754
- I squirmed because
there was strangers

23:27.797 --> 23:31.018
poking through my closets
and drawers.

23:31.061 --> 23:32.367
- Res ipsa loquitor.

23:32.411 --> 23:35.370
- My ex isn't "Ray,"
it's Zach.

23:35.414 --> 23:37.285
- Uh-huh.
It's Latin.

23:37.328 --> 23:39.287
It means "the thing speaks
for itself."

23:39.330 --> 23:41.376
As in, you had a skeleton
in your backyard,

23:41.420 --> 23:43.378
which means you probably had
something to do with it.

23:43.422 --> 23:44.727
- No.

23:44.771 --> 23:46.512
My ex did.

23:46.555 --> 23:49.515
And there's no way
you could prove otherwise.

23:49.558 --> 23:51.473
I've got some Latin for you:

23:51.517 --> 23:53.649
"Like father, like son."

23:53.693 --> 23:56.826
Maybe my son takes after
his old man.

24:00.177 --> 24:01.396
- Correct me if I'm wrong here,

24:01.440 --> 24:03.311
but did you just throw
your son under the bus?

24:03.354 --> 24:06.445
- It's hypothetical.

24:08.795 --> 24:10.536
- The body was
fully decomposed.

24:10.579 --> 24:13.582
Unless Emerson did this
when he was ten years old--

24:13.626 --> 24:15.976
I mean, it had to be
somebody much older.

24:16.019 --> 24:18.979
- Do we have anything
on Rowan's husband?

24:19.022 --> 24:20.197
- Zachary Mauer.

24:20.241 --> 24:22.635
He's had an open warrant
on an assault charge

24:22.678 --> 24:24.985
in New York State since '98.

24:25.028 --> 24:28.728
We're still working
on trying to locate him.

24:28.771 --> 24:30.207
- This could be the reason
he skipped town.

24:30.251 --> 24:31.557
- Hey, Liv.

24:31.600 --> 24:33.167
The lab ran the DNA

24:33.210 --> 24:35.343
from the t-shirt found
in the bedroom through NCMEC.

24:35.386 --> 24:37.084
We got a hit.
- Bailey?

24:37.127 --> 24:38.389
- No, Kevin Brown.

24:38.433 --> 24:40.870
He went missing
from Forest Park in 2002

24:40.914 --> 24:42.176
when he was six.

24:42.219 --> 24:44.047
- Does the DNA match the bones
in the backyard?

24:44.091 --> 24:45.092
- It's too soon to tell.

24:45.135 --> 24:47.921
He is survived
by his sister, Diane.

24:47.964 --> 24:50.619
- I hate this.

24:52.447 --> 24:54.928
- You're sure?

24:54.971 --> 24:57.234
- Pretty much.

24:57.278 --> 25:00.237
[somber music]

25:00.281 --> 25:02.805
♪

25:02.849 --> 25:06.505
- Our family was struggling...

25:06.548 --> 25:09.682
My dad was injured
working on Ladder 3.

25:09.725 --> 25:11.292
♪

25:11.335 --> 25:15.035
When I was 10,
Mom got Hodgkin's.

25:15.078 --> 25:16.950
Kevin was six.

25:16.993 --> 25:18.560
- I'm so sorry, Diane.

25:18.604 --> 25:21.563
- She said the cure was worse
than the disease.

25:21.607 --> 25:24.610
It was a struggle for her
to get out of bed.

25:24.653 --> 25:26.960
I was the big sister.

25:27.003 --> 25:29.136
When Dad was at work,

25:29.179 --> 25:30.746
I had to look after Kevin.

25:30.790 --> 25:34.881
I--I took him to daycare,
cooked dinner at night.

25:34.924 --> 25:38.188
When he had nightmares,
he slept in my bed.

25:38.232 --> 25:41.627
♪

25:41.670 --> 25:44.630
We were in the park
throwing a Frisbee.

25:44.673 --> 25:47.284
I went to get a Coke.

25:47.328 --> 25:49.112
The car was only
a few yards away

25:49.156 --> 25:52.333
from where we were playing.

25:52.376 --> 25:54.988
When I turned around,
Kevin was gone.

25:55.031 --> 25:58.339
- Diane, you were
ten years old, honey.

25:58.382 --> 25:59.601
This wasn't your fault.

25:59.645 --> 26:02.212
- Yes, it was.
[sniffles]

26:02.256 --> 26:04.519
But thanks.

26:04.563 --> 26:09.176
♪

26:09.219 --> 26:12.353
He's dead, isn't he?

26:12.396 --> 26:15.356
- [sighs]
We don't know for sure,

26:15.399 --> 26:19.273
but we think that we know
who took him.

26:19.316 --> 26:23.016
Do you know somebody
named Rowan Mauer?

26:23.059 --> 26:25.061
- No.

26:25.105 --> 26:29.413
♪

26:29.457 --> 26:32.416
Why would she take Kevin?

26:32.460 --> 26:37.291
♪

26:37.334 --> 26:38.945
- So Kevin and Diane Brown.

26:38.988 --> 26:42.035
This was taken two days
before Kevin went missing.

26:42.078 --> 26:44.646
Probably the last time
either of them smiled.

26:44.690 --> 26:45.952
- You spoke to Diane?

26:45.995 --> 26:47.649
- Yeah, she gave up hope
of finding her brother

26:47.693 --> 26:48.650
a long time ago.

26:48.694 --> 26:50.043
- Maybe that's a good thing.

26:50.086 --> 26:51.697
- We don't know those bones
belong to Kevin.

26:51.740 --> 26:53.176
- Oh, come on, we found
the kid's t-shirt

26:53.220 --> 26:54.874
in the Mauer house.

26:54.917 --> 26:56.789
- The lab is running DNA tests
on the skeleton right now.

26:56.832 --> 26:58.268
- I mean, what the hell,
I hope it is Kevin.

26:58.312 --> 26:59.487
At least then we have a shot

26:59.530 --> 27:00.880
of convicting Rowan Mauer
with something.

27:00.923 --> 27:02.533
- What, a public health
violation?

27:02.577 --> 27:04.361
She's gonna pay a fine
and walk.

27:04.405 --> 27:06.407
This family is--is Teflon.

27:06.450 --> 27:07.887
- Bailey still won't testify?

27:07.930 --> 27:10.280
- The dads are
dead-set against it.

27:10.324 --> 27:13.109
- Unfortunately, all of this
adds up to nothing.

27:13.153 --> 27:16.199
- So I have to tell Diane Brown
that we found her brother,

27:16.243 --> 27:17.897
we know who killed him,

27:17.940 --> 27:19.768
and there's nothing
that we can do about it?

27:19.812 --> 27:22.597
- We don't know
that skeleton's Kevin's.

27:22.641 --> 27:25.121
- Yet.

27:25.165 --> 27:26.470
What about a grand jury?

27:26.514 --> 27:27.907
- An indictment
without a conviction?

27:27.950 --> 27:29.952
That's just gonna
cause Diane more pain.

27:29.996 --> 27:31.693
- Okay, so...

27:31.737 --> 27:33.695
so two kids were kidnapped.

27:33.739 --> 27:36.089
One of them is dead,
and we have a legal system

27:36.132 --> 27:37.699
where we can't do anything
about it?

27:37.743 --> 27:41.007
What--what the hell
are we doing?

27:43.444 --> 27:44.575
- Hey, Liv?

27:44.619 --> 27:46.099
A grand jury might not be
such a bad idea.

27:46.142 --> 27:48.101
- A grand jury
investigating who?

27:48.144 --> 27:50.451
Bailey won't testify
against Emerson.

27:50.494 --> 27:51.626
- But Emerson's mother may.

27:51.670 --> 27:53.019
- She's just gonna
plead the fifth.

27:53.062 --> 27:54.760
- Not if I give her immunity
against being charged

27:54.803 --> 27:56.544
as an accomplice
in Bailey's kidnapping.

27:56.587 --> 27:57.893
If she happens
to implicate herself

27:57.937 --> 27:59.286
in Kevin Brown's kidnapping
and murder, so be it.

27:59.329 --> 28:01.984
- Do you really think
that a mother is gonna testify

28:02.028 --> 28:03.551
against her son?

28:03.594 --> 28:06.902
- Her son, the pedophile.

28:10.427 --> 28:12.473
- I came home early.

28:12.516 --> 28:15.606
There was a problem
with the internet.

28:15.650 --> 28:18.131
- So your son didn't know
you'd be home?

28:18.174 --> 28:19.219
- No.

28:19.262 --> 28:22.439
Usually I work late.

28:22.483 --> 28:23.789
- And it was his day off?

28:23.832 --> 28:27.053
- [sighs]
Yeah.

28:27.096 --> 28:29.882
- What did you find
when you got home, Mrs. Mauer?

28:31.535 --> 28:33.494
- It was quiet.

28:33.537 --> 28:35.975
I thought Em was out.

28:36.018 --> 28:38.194
I went upstairs to change.

28:38.238 --> 28:40.806
I saw...

28:40.849 --> 28:43.678
the light in his room was on.

28:43.722 --> 28:45.767
I don't how many times
I told him

28:45.811 --> 28:48.161
electricity doesn't grow
on trees.

28:48.204 --> 28:49.728
- So...

28:49.771 --> 28:51.817
you went to the room...

28:51.860 --> 28:54.733
to turn off the light?

28:56.386 --> 28:57.648
- That's right.

28:57.692 --> 28:59.912
- And what did you see?

29:01.217 --> 29:03.959
[tense music]

29:04.003 --> 29:07.093
What did you see
in your son's room, Mrs. Mauer?

29:07.136 --> 29:14.187
♪

29:15.014 --> 29:18.365
Let me remind you
that if you refuse to answer,

29:18.408 --> 29:20.889
any arrangement for immunity
that you made with my office

29:20.933 --> 29:23.109
will be null and void.

29:23.152 --> 29:26.677
♪

29:26.721 --> 29:30.725
- I saw my son in bed.

29:30.769 --> 29:33.032
- Was he alone?

29:33.075 --> 29:35.077
♪

29:35.121 --> 29:36.644
- No.

29:36.687 --> 29:38.646
He was...

29:38.689 --> 29:41.214
with a little girl.

29:41.257 --> 29:43.607
♪

29:43.651 --> 29:46.567
- What did you do?

29:46.610 --> 29:48.612
- I told him...

29:48.656 --> 29:51.877
to take her back
where he found her.

29:51.920 --> 29:53.879
He carried her down the stairs.

29:53.922 --> 29:56.751
She was still sleeping.

29:56.795 --> 29:59.232
I--I told him to put her
in the trunk

29:59.275 --> 30:02.235
so she wouldn't know
where she was if she woke up.

30:02.278 --> 30:04.454
- Then what happened?

30:04.498 --> 30:06.500
- He took off.

30:06.543 --> 30:08.415
♪

30:08.458 --> 30:10.591
And about forty minutes later,

30:10.634 --> 30:14.638
he came back without the car.

30:14.682 --> 30:17.424
He said...

30:17.467 --> 30:19.600
[sighs]

30:19.643 --> 30:22.516
When he stopped
to get the girl candy,

30:22.559 --> 30:25.258
somebody stole his car.

30:25.301 --> 30:28.261
- With Bailey Shaw
still in the trunk?

30:28.304 --> 30:32.613
♪

30:32.656 --> 30:35.877
- That's what he said.

30:35.921 --> 30:38.271
- Thank you, Mrs. Mauer.

30:38.314 --> 30:40.577
That'll be all for now.

30:40.621 --> 30:47.846
♪

30:50.196 --> 30:53.460
[indistinct chatter,
phones ringing]

31:11.826 --> 31:14.307
- I have blue eyes.

31:14.350 --> 31:15.569
- Congratulations?

31:15.612 --> 31:18.093
- Al has blue eyes,
Billie has blue eyes.

31:18.137 --> 31:20.704
- Okay, if I remember
my high school bio correctly,

31:20.748 --> 31:22.924
it's called a recessive gene.

31:22.968 --> 31:25.318
- Look at this.

31:25.361 --> 31:27.233
♪

31:27.276 --> 31:31.324
Zach and Rowan
both have brown eyes.

31:31.367 --> 31:34.153
- Emerson has blue.

31:34.196 --> 31:36.720
♪

31:36.764 --> 31:38.592
- I know it's a stretch, but--

31:38.635 --> 31:40.507
- Statistically speaking,

31:40.550 --> 31:43.162
Emerson may not be Rowan's son.

31:43.205 --> 31:46.339
♪

31:46.382 --> 31:49.646
[scoffs]

31:49.690 --> 31:52.519
Peter, it's me.

31:55.043 --> 31:55.261
.

31:55.304 --> 31:58.046
- Well, when the world's
going to crap, the one thing

31:58.090 --> 31:59.743
that lifts my spirits are
Mama Carisi's famous cannolis.

31:59.787 --> 32:01.528
- I may have something better.
- Nothing works better.

32:01.571 --> 32:04.183
- How about a DNA map?

32:04.226 --> 32:06.968
- Let me guess,
the, uh, skeleton we found

32:07.012 --> 32:08.535
in the Mauer's backyard
is Kevin Brown.

32:08.578 --> 32:09.579
- You're gonna have
to guess again,

32:09.623 --> 32:11.320
because there is
a maternal match.

32:11.364 --> 32:13.409
99% chance that the kid
in the yard

32:13.453 --> 32:15.585
was Rowan Mauer's son.

32:15.629 --> 32:17.413
- What?
- Yeah.

32:17.457 --> 32:19.067
- Emerson had a brother?

32:19.111 --> 32:22.505
- No, not according
to any public records.

32:22.549 --> 32:24.594
- Are you saying
that the body that we dug up,

32:24.638 --> 32:26.161
that's Emerson Mauer?

32:26.205 --> 32:27.946
- Yeah.

32:27.989 --> 32:29.730
- [scoffs]
Hold--hold on.

32:29.773 --> 32:31.079
I--I'm a little confused here,

32:31.123 --> 32:33.603
because if Emerson
is dead and buried,

32:33.647 --> 32:36.780
then who the hell
kidnapped Bailey?

32:38.869 --> 32:41.524
No way.
- That's what I said.

32:41.568 --> 32:45.746
- All right, you call Liv,
I'll call Stone.

32:45.789 --> 32:48.096
- Uh, excuse me, we had a deal.

32:48.140 --> 32:50.229
She testifies against Emerson,
she gets immunity.

32:50.272 --> 32:52.535
- The deal was conditioned upon
your client telling the truth.

32:52.579 --> 32:55.321
- I did.
- You called him your son.

32:55.364 --> 32:58.106
- We know that's a lie.

32:58.150 --> 33:02.415
'Cause your son died
17 years ago.

33:02.458 --> 33:04.025
- Too bad you can't prove it.

33:04.069 --> 33:06.071
- Well, the lab is testing
the DNA of the man

33:06.114 --> 33:07.986
pretending to be your son
as we speak.

33:08.029 --> 33:09.988
- They're gonna call me
with the results.

33:10.031 --> 33:12.033
You've got until then
to make a deal, Mrs. Mauer.

33:12.077 --> 33:13.295
- For what?

33:13.339 --> 33:14.731
- She testified that
she was an accomplice

33:14.775 --> 33:16.603
to Bailey's kidnapping,

33:16.646 --> 33:18.866
so when the DNA comes back

33:18.909 --> 33:21.825
and it matches Kevin Brown's...

33:21.869 --> 33:25.525
there's gonna be
another kidnapping charge.

33:25.568 --> 33:28.745
- And a murder.
- Who did she kill?

33:28.789 --> 33:30.617
- Her own son...

33:30.660 --> 33:34.012
the real Emerson,
17 years ago.

33:36.492 --> 33:39.539
- Tick, tock.

33:39.582 --> 33:40.714
- What's in it for her?

33:40.757 --> 33:43.064
- I'm thinking 20 years.

33:43.108 --> 33:46.067
[tense music]

33:46.111 --> 33:48.461
♪

33:48.504 --> 33:51.638
- Of course that's not my son.

33:51.681 --> 33:54.206
My son wouldn't be
stupid enough

33:54.249 --> 33:55.511
to grab a little girl.

33:55.555 --> 33:58.166
- Then what happened
to the real Emerson?

33:58.210 --> 34:01.604
♪

34:01.648 --> 34:04.607
- [sighs]
Zach and I...

34:04.651 --> 34:06.914
had a disagreement.

34:06.957 --> 34:08.829
- A fight.
- Stop, Rowan.

34:08.872 --> 34:12.093
- No, what choice do I have?

34:12.137 --> 34:14.661
♪

34:14.704 --> 34:18.839
We were at the top
of the stairs.

34:18.882 --> 34:22.538
We didn't know
Emerson was behind us.

34:22.582 --> 34:25.628
Zach pushed me.

34:25.672 --> 34:27.543
I bumped into my son

34:27.587 --> 34:31.373
and he fell down the stairs.

34:31.417 --> 34:33.201
He broke his neck.

34:33.245 --> 34:36.248
There was blood
coming out of his ears.

34:36.291 --> 34:41.557
♪

34:41.601 --> 34:43.342
[whimpers]

34:43.385 --> 34:47.085
It was an accident.

34:47.128 --> 34:48.521
♪

34:48.564 --> 34:50.392
- And why didn't you call
the police?

34:50.436 --> 34:52.481
- We were drinking.

34:52.525 --> 34:54.701
Zach was a rager.

34:54.744 --> 34:57.138
He had assault charges.

34:57.182 --> 35:00.489
They would have thought
we killed him.

35:00.533 --> 35:04.406
We had no other choice.

35:04.450 --> 35:08.280
♪

35:08.323 --> 35:12.588
I buried my sweet baby...

35:12.632 --> 35:15.113
in the backyard.

35:15.156 --> 35:17.115
♪

35:17.158 --> 35:21.249
- And Kevin Brown
was the perfect replacement.

35:21.293 --> 35:25.253
Same age, same height
and weight.

35:25.297 --> 35:28.169
- [sniffles]
And...

35:28.213 --> 35:29.649
♪

35:29.692 --> 35:32.217
Zach left a week later.

35:32.260 --> 35:36.612
♪

35:36.656 --> 35:39.311
- So you raised Kevin
as your own.

35:39.354 --> 35:46.405
♪

35:50.844 --> 35:53.194
- [sighs]

35:53.238 --> 35:56.241
♪

35:56.284 --> 36:00.419
- This is Diane Brown,
Kevin's sister.

36:00.462 --> 36:03.509
You remember her?
- [gasps]

36:03.552 --> 36:06.642
What are you doing here?

36:06.686 --> 36:08.601
♪

36:08.644 --> 36:11.038
I did you a favor.

36:11.081 --> 36:14.868
Your parents didn't care
anything about either of you.

36:14.911 --> 36:16.783
- What are you talking about?

36:16.826 --> 36:18.828
- They let you run
all over the city

36:18.872 --> 36:20.265
like a couple of ragamuffins.

36:20.308 --> 36:22.484
When you were coming
to the store to get ice cream,

36:22.528 --> 36:23.659
you were all alone.

36:23.703 --> 36:27.010
You were ten, he was six.

36:27.054 --> 36:30.840
What kind of mother does that?

36:30.884 --> 36:33.582
- One who was dying.

36:33.626 --> 36:36.194
♪

36:36.237 --> 36:38.674
- Better yet.

36:38.718 --> 36:40.763
Kevin had a good life with me.

36:40.807 --> 36:44.202
I fed him, I clothed him,

36:44.245 --> 36:46.552
I loved him.

36:46.595 --> 36:48.771
He had a mom.

36:48.815 --> 36:50.904
♪

36:50.947 --> 36:53.080
- You stole him.

36:53.123 --> 36:55.387
- But my baby was dead.

36:55.430 --> 36:57.389
I deserved--
- No.

36:57.432 --> 36:59.652
No.

36:59.695 --> 37:01.915
No one...

37:01.958 --> 37:05.875
deserves somebody else's child.

37:05.919 --> 37:13.143
♪

37:14.754 --> 37:16.495
- No, okay?
That can't be true.

37:16.538 --> 37:19.193
I am Emerson Mauer, okay?

37:19.237 --> 37:21.369
- I know how hard
this is to hear, Kevin--

37:21.413 --> 37:23.980
- Don't call me that.
- You have a sister, Diane.

37:24.024 --> 37:26.592
- No, it's just me and my mom.

37:26.635 --> 37:29.029
- Diane took care you.
- My mom took care of me.

37:29.072 --> 37:30.465
- Your mother was sick.

37:30.509 --> 37:32.467
She had Hodgkin's.

37:32.511 --> 37:33.947
She was sick in bed,

37:33.990 --> 37:35.427
and your father
was working all the time.

37:35.470 --> 37:37.298
- Why are you lying to me?
- I'm not.

37:37.342 --> 37:39.605
Think,
Just think, Kevin, think.

37:39.648 --> 37:43.522
♪

37:43.565 --> 37:46.438
Diane used to take you
to get ice cream.

37:46.481 --> 37:47.830
She used to take you

37:47.874 --> 37:49.092
to the park, right?

37:49.136 --> 37:52.400
To play Frisbee.

37:52.444 --> 37:55.403
And you had nightmares
as a little boy, didn't you?

37:55.447 --> 37:58.188
And it was Diane's bed
that you crawled into

37:58.232 --> 37:59.668
because she held you.

37:59.712 --> 38:01.104
She made you feel safe

38:01.148 --> 38:03.977
because she loved you so much.

38:04.020 --> 38:06.196
And you loved her.

38:06.240 --> 38:10.984
♪

38:11.027 --> 38:12.159
- No, no, no, no,

38:12.202 --> 38:14.030
'cause if that was true
I would remember.

38:14.074 --> 38:17.599
- You do remember, Kevin.
- No!

38:17.643 --> 38:20.428
No!

38:20.472 --> 38:24.954
♪

38:24.998 --> 38:27.566
- Do you know what I think?

38:27.609 --> 38:30.830
♪

38:30.873 --> 38:33.615
I think that...

38:33.659 --> 38:36.139
that deep down in your heart,

38:36.183 --> 38:39.534
and in your mind,
and in your subconscious...

38:39.578 --> 38:41.797
your sister's alive...

38:41.841 --> 38:43.495
and taking care of you.

38:43.538 --> 38:45.323
- I don't have a sister.

38:45.366 --> 38:46.802
- And you just wanted
to reach out to her

38:46.846 --> 38:49.936
and have her hold you
because you miss her so much.

38:49.979 --> 38:52.330
- That is crazy.
- That's why you took Bailey.

38:52.373 --> 38:54.810
You didn't want to hurt her.
I know that.

38:54.854 --> 38:58.466
You wanted to take care of her.

38:58.510 --> 39:00.860
Like your sister
took care of you.

39:00.903 --> 39:02.644
- No, okay?

39:02.688 --> 39:04.994
I am Emerson Mauer!

39:05.038 --> 39:07.040
[stammers]

39:07.083 --> 39:09.347
Just--just leave me alone,
all right?

39:09.390 --> 39:11.479
You're a liar.

39:11.523 --> 39:15.875
♪

39:15.918 --> 39:19.618
I don't want to talk anymore.

39:19.661 --> 39:21.663
[gasps]

39:21.707 --> 39:28.714
♪

39:32.892 --> 39:35.851
[indistinct muttering,
heavy breathing]

39:35.895 --> 39:38.506
[weeping]

39:38.550 --> 39:41.466
[door alarm buzzes]

39:41.509 --> 39:43.250
[keys jangling]

39:43.293 --> 39:45.861
- Diane.
Wait, please.

39:45.905 --> 39:48.168
Diane, it's gonna
come back to him.

39:48.211 --> 39:50.213
I promise you,
with--with counseling--

39:50.257 --> 39:52.041
- What's the point?

39:52.085 --> 39:54.130
- The point is that the DA
is gonna cut him a deal.

39:54.174 --> 39:57.307
- He's not my brother anymore.

39:57.351 --> 40:00.049
♪

40:00.093 --> 40:02.269
He stopped being my brother
17 years ago.

40:02.312 --> 40:04.445
- This is just gonna take time.
- We're people.

40:04.489 --> 40:07.230
We're not a broken vase
you can put together

40:07.274 --> 40:09.711
with a little Krazy Glue.

40:09.755 --> 40:11.017
- Diane--

40:11.060 --> 40:12.453
- Look, I know
you think you're doing

40:12.497 --> 40:14.063
doing the right thing,
Lieutenant,

40:14.107 --> 40:16.979
and maybe for someone else
it would be...

40:17.023 --> 40:19.373
♪

40:19.417 --> 40:22.811
But I'm just not that strong.

40:22.855 --> 40:27.729
♪

40:27.773 --> 40:29.688
[sobs]

40:29.731 --> 40:31.864
[sniffles]

40:31.907 --> 40:34.432
[door alarm buzzes]

40:34.475 --> 40:41.439
♪

40:49.185 --> 40:49.403
.

40:49.447 --> 40:52.101
[dramatic music]

40:52.145 --> 40:59.369
♪

41:18.563 --> 41:21.566
[wolf howls]
